<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1977]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">
Legs short and robust. Protarsi with four slender and not dilated segments in both sexes, first protarsomere slightly longer than second and third, fourth longest. Mesotarsi and metatarsi pentamerous in both sexes. Claws simple, well-developed and sharp, empodium with one bifurcate seta. Protibiae flattened, armed with spines (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1837,1861]" captionTargetBox="[163,1426,188,1803]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[151,1436,181,1814]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Bathyscidius basarai sp. nov. 1: Habitus, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.90 mm. 2: Venter, median longitudinal carina in metaventrite, without scale bar. 3: Antennae, female antenna (3a), male antenna (3b), dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.10 mm. 4: Female right protibia, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.268 mm. 5: Aedeagus, dorsal (5a) and right lateral (5b) aspects, scale bar 0.08 mm. 6: Male genital segment, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.202 mm. 7: Female urite VIII, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.297 mm. 8: Female genital segments—styles, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.13 mm. 9: Spermatheca, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.107 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4491313" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4491313/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), on external lateral and apical side with the row of flattened spines forming a comb (pecten) reaching apical half of tibial length, internal subapical side with one simple spur and one internal apical multi-toothed spur. Mesotibiae and metatibiae cylindrical, armed with lateral spines, with apical crown of spines of unequal length (
<bibRefCitation author="Gnaspini, P. &amp; Peck, S. B. &amp; Antunes-Carvalho, C. &amp; Perreau, M. &amp; Gomyde, E. C." pageId="4" pageNumber="592" pagination="1 - 12" refId="ref4259" refString="Gnaspini, P., Peck, S. B., Antunes-Carvalho, C., Perreau, M. &amp; Gomyde, E. C. (2020) To be or not to be a tibial comb: A dis- cussion on the (past) use of tibial armature in tribal / subtribal organization in Cholevinae (Coleoptera: Leiodidae). Papeis Avulsos de Zoologia, Museu de Zoologia da Universidade de Sao Paulo, 60, 1 - 12. https: // doi. org / 10.11606 / 1807 - 0205 / 2020.60. special-issue. 18" type="journal article" year="2020">
Gnaspini 
<emphasis box="[1381,1437,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
) and one internal apical multi-toothed spur. Femora surface reticulated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1977]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">
Male genital segment (
<figureCitation box="[466,538,403,430]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1837,1861]" captionTargetBox="[163,1426,188,1803]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[151,1436,181,1814]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Bathyscidius basarai sp. nov. 1: Habitus, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.90 mm. 2: Venter, median longitudinal carina in metaventrite, without scale bar. 3: Antennae, female antenna (3a), male antenna (3b), dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.10 mm. 4: Female right protibia, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.268 mm. 5: Aedeagus, dorsal (5a) and right lateral (5b) aspects, scale bar 0.08 mm. 6: Male genital segment, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.202 mm. 7: Female urite VIII, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.297 mm. 8: Female genital segments—styles, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.13 mm. 9: Spermatheca, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.107 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4491313" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4491313/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[689,822,402,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1837,1861]" captionTargetBox="[163,1426,188,1803]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[151,1436,181,1814]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Bathyscidius basarai sp. nov. 1: Habitus, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.90 mm. 2: Venter, median longitudinal carina in metaventrite, without scale bar. 3: Antennae, female antenna (3a), male antenna (3b), dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.10 mm. 4: Female right protibia, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.268 mm. 5: Aedeagus, dorsal (5a) and right lateral (5b) aspects, scale bar 0.08 mm. 6: Male genital segment, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.202 mm. 7: Female urite VIII, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.297 mm. 8: Female genital segments—styles, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.13 mm. 9: Spermatheca, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.107 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4491313" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4491313/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Figs 5a, 5b</figureCitation>
) small, 
<quantity box="[919,1023,403,429]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" unit="mm" value="0.38">0.38 mm</quantity>
long, fairly elongated. Inner sac of median lobe lacking sclerotized structures or dorsal flagellum. Median lobe almost straight from dorsal aspect, extended in apical third, slowly narrowed towards moderately pointed apex which is markedly beak-shaped. Median lobe more or less straight in lateral aspect, only slightly curved in mid length and at apex, which is rounded. Median lobe in apical part with two lateral dorsally first straight and after convergent longitudinal lobes. Average length of basal lamina 
<quantity box="[301,404,583,609]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" unit="mm" value="0.08">0.08 mm</quantity>
, almost parallel with median lobe, simply rounded, lacking posterior expansion. Parameres parallel-sided, more or less straight, slightly curved in apical third, slightly shorter than median lobe, bearing three long subapical setae close to each other, sligthly exceeding apex of median lobe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1977]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">
Female ventrite VIII densely pubescent in proximal part with anterior expansion stout (
<figureCitation box="[160,229,727,753]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1837,1861]" captionTargetBox="[163,1426,188,1803]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[151,1436,181,1814]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Bathyscidius basarai sp. nov. 1: Habitus, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.90 mm. 2: Venter, median longitudinal carina in metaventrite, without scale bar. 3: Antennae, female antenna (3a), male antenna (3b), dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.10 mm. 4: Female right protibia, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.268 mm. 5: Aedeagus, dorsal (5a) and right lateral (5b) aspects, scale bar 0.08 mm. 6: Male genital segment, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.202 mm. 7: Female urite VIII, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.297 mm. 8: Female genital segments—styles, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.13 mm. 9: Spermatheca, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.107 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4491313" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4491313/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Stylomeres (
<figureCitation box="[395,462,727,753]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1837,1861]" captionTargetBox="[163,1426,188,1803]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[151,1436,181,1814]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Bathyscidius basarai sp. nov. 1: Habitus, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.90 mm. 2: Venter, median longitudinal carina in metaventrite, without scale bar. 3: Antennae, female antenna (3a), male antenna (3b), dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.10 mm. 4: Female right protibia, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.268 mm. 5: Aedeagus, dorsal (5a) and right lateral (5b) aspects, scale bar 0.08 mm. 6: Male genital segment, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.202 mm. 7: Female urite VIII, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.297 mm. 8: Female genital segments—styles, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.13 mm. 9: Spermatheca, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.107 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4491313" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4491313/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) parallel-sided and relatively narrow. Stylomeres with more or less straight inner and outer edges. Gonocoxite with 3-4 setae, sub-gonocoxite with two lateral setae and one subapical seta, gonostylus with one seta which is longest. Spermatheca (
<figureCitation box="[662,730,799,825]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1837,1861]" captionTargetBox="[163,1426,188,1803]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[151,1436,181,1814]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Bathyscidius basarai sp. nov. 1: Habitus, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.90 mm. 2: Venter, median longitudinal carina in metaventrite, without scale bar. 3: Antennae, female antenna (3a), male antenna (3b), dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.10 mm. 4: Female right protibia, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.268 mm. 5: Aedeagus, dorsal (5a) and right lateral (5b) aspects, scale bar 0.08 mm. 6: Male genital segment, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.202 mm. 7: Female urite VIII, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.297 mm. 8: Female genital segments—styles, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.13 mm. 9: Spermatheca, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.107 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4491313" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4491313/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1977]" box="[199,586,835,861]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Sexual dimorphism: Not apparent.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="592" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1977]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,625,870,897]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Differential diagnosis and remarks.</emphasis>
Distinct protibial external latero-apical comb (pecten) extending to approximately apical half of protibial length is the intermediate character state within the genus as distinct comb extending to two apical thirds of the protibial length in 
<emphasis box="[783,1013,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jeannel" authorityYear="1910" box="[783,926,943,969]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Bathyscidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Bathyscidius</taxonomicName>
(s. str.)
</emphasis>
and less strong comb is extending to apical third of the protibial length in the subgenus 
<emphasis box="[720,1162,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Polak &amp; Jalzic" authorityYear="2019" box="[720,915,979,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Bathyscidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Ionobathyscidius">Ionobathyscidius</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Čeplík &amp; Lakota &amp; Čeplík, 2021" authorityName="Čeplík &amp; Lakota &amp; Čeplík" authorityYear="2021" box="[926,1162,979,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Bathyscidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basarai" status="sp. nov.">Bathyscidius basarai</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1169,1259,979,1005]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1169,1259,979,1005]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
differs from all other species of the genus by the median longitudinal carina extended to the metaventrite where it is slightly shorter and its posterior beak is not reaching the bifid posterior metaventral process (
<figureCitation box="[1003,1071,1051,1077]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1837,1861]" captionTargetBox="[163,1426,188,1803]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[151,1436,181,1814]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Bathyscidius basarai sp. nov. 1: Habitus, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.90 mm. 2: Venter, median longitudinal carina in metaventrite, without scale bar. 3: Antennae, female antenna (3a), male antenna (3b), dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.10 mm. 4: Female right protibia, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.268 mm. 5: Aedeagus, dorsal (5a) and right lateral (5b) aspects, scale bar 0.08 mm. 6: Male genital segment, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.202 mm. 7: Female urite VIII, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.297 mm. 8: Female genital segments—styles, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.13 mm. 9: Spermatheca, dorsal aspect, scale bar 0.107 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4491313" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4491313/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). In all other species of both subgenera the median longitudinal carina is slightly longer with the posterior beak almost reaching the bifid posterior metaventral process. Further it differs from all members of the nominal subgenus by pointed beak-shaped apex of median lobe and parameres bearing three subapical setae. In nominal subgenus the median lobe is simply rounded or it is subtriangular, parameres are bearing one apical and two lateral setae. Due to the similarity of the median lobe, the new species is tentatively assigned to the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Polak &amp; Jalzic" authorityYear="2019" box="[769,960,1231,1257]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Bathyscidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Ionobathyscidius">
<emphasis box="[769,960,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Ionobathyscidius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1977]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">
Other nominal 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Polak &amp; Jalzic" authorityYear="2019" box="[376,740,1267,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Bathyscidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Ionobathyscidius">
<emphasis box="[376,740,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Bathyscidius (Ionobathyscidius)</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species can be separated from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Čeplík &amp; Lakota &amp; Čeplík" authorityYear="2021" box="[1111,1351,1267,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Bathyscidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basarai">
<emphasis box="[1111,1351,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Bathyscidius basarai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as follows:
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1977]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">
<emphasis box="[199,727,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">
- 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muller" authorityYear="1922" box="[216,727,1339,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Bathyscidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tomoricensis" subGenus="Ionobathyscidius">Bathyscidius (Ionobathyscidius) tomoricensis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
by: median lobe lacking visible longitudinal lobes (versus two long lobes in new species); extremely long basal lamina (versus comparatively short in new species); stylomeres with basally concave outer and moderately convex inner edges (versus more or less straight in new species).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1977]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">
<emphasis box="[199,714,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">
- 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Knirsch" authorityYear="1930" box="[216,714,1447,1473]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Bathyscidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rambouseki" subGenus="Ionobathyscidius">Bathyscidius (Ionobathyscidius) rambouseki</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
by: shorter apex of median lobe (versus longer and beak-shaped in new species); lateral longitudinal lobes significantly shorter and divergent in median lobe (versus long and convergent in new species); stylomeres basally concave or straight outer and moderately convex inner edges (versus more or less straight in new species).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="592" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1977]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1591,1617]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Etymology.</emphasis>
Dedicated to our dear friend Damir Basara (Karlovac, 
<collectingCountry box="[944,1031,1591,1618]" name="Croatia" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Croatia</collectingCountry>
), instructor of speleology, and member of our speleobiological team during researches in 
<collectingCountry box="[751,843,1627,1653]" name="Albania" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Albania</collectingCountry>
. Gender masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="592" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1977]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,592,1662,1689]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Distribution and natural history.</emphasis>
The new species is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[1064,1112,1663,1689]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">type</typeStatus>
locality, the Shpella e Blazit cave (
<figureCitation box="[218,384,1699,1725]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–13" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1833,1857]" captionTargetBox="[160,1431,316,1797]" captionTargetId="figure-86@3.[151,1436,309,1810]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 10–13. 10: The cave Shpella e Blazit, the entrance—green arrow. 11: Shpella e Blazit, on the entrance. 12: Shpella e Blazit, topographical sketch. 13: Distribution of the genus Bathyscidius—Bathyscidius (s.str.), four species from Croatia (1- 4), one species from Montenegro (5); Bathyscidius (Ionobathyscidius), one species from Albania (7), one species from North Macedonia (6), Bathyscidius basarai sp. nov. from Albania (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4491315" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4491315/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Figs 10, 11, 12</figureCitation>
), coordinates 
<geoCoordinate box="[540,701,1699,1725]" degrees="41" direction="north" minutes="42" orientation="latitude" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" precision="1" seconds="17.9" value="41.70497">41°42‘17.9“N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[712,867,1698,1725]" degrees="20" direction="east" minutes="00" orientation="longitude" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" precision="1" seconds="28.5" value="20.007917">20°00‘28.5“E</geoCoordinate>
(WGS 84), situated at the elevation of 
<quantity box="[1301,1371,1699,1725]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" unit="m" value="280.0">280 m</quantity>
a.s.l., approximately one km northeast of the village Bruç in the Central 
<collectingCountry box="[906,998,1735,1761]" name="Albania" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Albania</collectingCountry>
. The cave is located above the village, at the end of the limestone valley on the left side. The entrance is visible from the valley between limestone rocks. One main chamber is approximately 
<quantity box="[573,632,1807,1833]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" unit="m" value="70.0">70 m</quantity>
long, and 
<quantity box="[754,822,1807,1833]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" unit="m" value="7.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="7.0">7-8 m</quantity>
wide, with depth 
<quantity box="[1029,1100,1806,1833]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" unit="m" value="4.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="4.0">
4- 
<specimenCount box="[1053,1100,1806,1833]" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" type="generic">5 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
. The mud bottom of the cave is covered with rocks and stones of various dimensions. Specimens were found in many places from the middle to the end of the cave main chamber. They were collected under stones, but mainly on cave walls to maximum of 0,5 m above the bottom surface, which was only partially covered with bat guano deposit. This cave is also a point of interest for Paleolithic archaeology research. Distribution map for the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jeannel" authorityYear="1910" box="[1009,1152,1951,1977]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Bathyscidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="592" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1009,1152,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Bathyscidius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is given (
<figureCitation box="[1262,1345,1951,1977]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–13" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1833,1857]" captionTargetBox="[160,1431,316,1797]" captionTargetId="figure-86@3.[151,1436,309,1810]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 10–13. 10: The cave Shpella e Blazit, the entrance—green arrow. 11: Shpella e Blazit, on the entrance. 12: Shpella e Blazit, topographical sketch. 13: Distribution of the genus Bathyscidius—Bathyscidius (s.str.), four species from Croatia (1- 4), one species from Montenegro (5); Bathyscidius (Ionobathyscidius), one species from Albania (7), one species from North Macedonia (6), Bathyscidius basarai sp. nov. from Albania (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4491315" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4491315/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="592">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
).
